DcyLjPmtVhoVJVELwlEODYuMQAAAAAQ85he&p=bala+junction+railway+station&fr=mcafee&fr2=sb-top-uk.images.search.yahoo.com&ei=UTF-8&n=60&x=wrt&y=Search Images of the station, via ''Yahoo'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PX28cjuE-Zo Driver's view north of Bala to Blaenau, via ''YouTube'']\n* [http://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-a-passenger-train-leaving-bala-station-on-the-bala-blaenau-ffestiniog-83556080.html Train leaving Bala station, via ''alamy'']\n* [http://www.penmorfa.com/Conwy/seven.htm Several photos of the Blaenau line, via ''Penmorfa'']\n* [http://www.penmorfa.com/Conwy/nine.htm Several photos of the Blaenau line, via ''Penmorfa'']\n* [http://www.2d53.co.uk/blaenauffestiniog/Trawsfynydd%20Branch%203.htm A special on the Blaenau line, via ''2D53'']\n* [http://www.2d53.co.uk/TT/TTBJBF60HMD1.htm 1960 [[Working timetable]], via ''2D53'']\n* [http://www.sixbellsjunction.co.uk/80s/890723br.htm Details of Summer 1989 excursions through the station, via ''Six Bells Junction'']\n* [http://www.sixbellsjunction.co.uk/ Deatails and photos of 22 Jan 1961 railtour, via ''Six Bells Junction'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lt09amW1n9I The 1961 last train special, via ''YouTube'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5737kTu8l7k An inspection saloon ride on the line, Part 1, via ''YouTube'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=od0Q63YTRgk An inspection saloon ride on the line, Part 2, via ''YouTube'']\n* [http://www.s-r-s.org.uk/html/gww/S3270.htm Signal box diagram, via ''Signalling Record Society'']\n\n{{Closed stations Gwynedd}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bala Junction Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1882]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1965]]\n[[Category:Former Great Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Rail junctions in Wales]]\n[[Category:Llangywer]]\n[[Category:Bala, Gwynedd]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in Gwynedd, Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name       = Bala Junction\n|image      = [[File:Bala junction 1 rail station 1862659 cee1bc98.jpg|300px]]\n|caption    = Bala Junction station in 1962\n|pregroup   = [[Great Western Railway]]\n|locale     = [[Bala, Gwynedd|Bala]]\n|borough    = [[Gwynedd]]\n| gridref   = SH 937 355\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.90640|-3.58150|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|platforms  = 3{{sfn|Southern|1995|pp=1, 19-24 & 101}}{{sfn|Mitchell|Smith|2010|loc=Map III and Photos 1-3}}{{sfn|Turner|2003|p=16}}\n|years      = 1 November 1882\n|events     = Opened{{sfn|Boyd|1988|p=47}}\n|years1     = 18 January 1965{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=22}}{{sfn|Quick|2009|p=70}}\n|events1    = Closed to passengers\n}}\n{{Bala and Festiniog Railway|collapse=yes}}\n{{Ruabon to Barmouth Line|collapse=yes}}\n'''Bala Junction railway station''' was on the [[Ruabon Barmouth Line|Ruabon to Barmouth line]] in southern [[Gwynedd]], Wales.{{sfn|Jowett|2000|loc=Map 45}} It closed to passengers on Monday 18 January 1965. Bala Junction was unusual in that it was inaccessible by road{{sfn|Clemens|2003|loc=8 and 10 mins from start}} and merely served as an interchange station; it was located about \u00be mile to the south-east of the town of Bala.\n\nThe station was at the junction with the [[Bala Ffestiniog Line|Blaenau Ffestiniog branch]]. It was built as a crossing point for trains on the Bala Ffestiniog and Ruabon Barmouth lines, and featured three platforms with a small waiting room and signalbox on a central island platform. There was also a cast-iron GWR water tank.{{sfn|Baughan|1980|p=88}}\n\n==History==\n\nOpened by the [[Great Western Railway]], it remained in that company through the [[Railways Act 1921|Grouping]] of 1923. The station passed to the [[Western Region of British Railways]] on [[nationalisation]] in 1948. Passenger services to Bala and on the Ruabon-Barmouth line ceased in January 1965; the service beyond Bala to Blaenau Festiniog having been withdrawn in 1960.\n\nDuring its operational life, Bala Junction served as an interchange station for the branch line train to Blaenau Festiniog, usually operated by small tank locomotives such as the [[GWR 6400 Class|6400 Class]] 0-6-0PT and [[GWR 5800 Class|5800 Class]] 0-4-2T tank locomotives. These trains did not run beyond Bala Junction, instead returning north to the GWR station at Blaenau Festiniog. There were no goods facilities here either; all goods trains stopped to shunt detached wagons for the branch line train.\n\nAs a junction station, Bala Junction was equipped with standard GWR lower quadrant semaphore signals to control train movements between the Bala Ffestiniog and Ruabon-Barmouth lines. These were used particularly when the branch line train was shunting in preparation for its return to Blaenau Festiniog as there were no turning facilities here. To run around, the branch line engine had to cross from Platform 3 (the Bala Ffestiniog platform) onto the main line and run back along Platform 2, used by eastbound trains running to Ruabon.\n\nAs of 2014, the only remnants at Bala Junction are the trackbeds of the Bala Ffestiniog and Ruabon-Barmouth lines and the platform faces. The site is close to a nearby dam; part of the access road for this uses the formation of the Bala Ffestiniog line, passing close to the remains of a short bridge that carried the line into Bala Junction itself.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Bala junction 3 rail station 1862718 d26261ee.jpg|BR Standard 4MT 75028 arrives at Bala Junction with the 12.45 Pwllheli-Chester.\nFile:Bala junction 2 rail station 1862718 d26261ee.jpg|View NE from the station along the Ruabon Barmouth Line.\n</gallery>\n\n==Neighbouring stations==\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Llandderfel railway station|Llandderfel]]<br><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|next=[[Bala Lake Halt railway station|Bala Lake Halt]]<br><s